        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Thanks for the issue!\n\n> ```\n> nvim --clean\n> :lua vim.pack.add({{src=\"https://github.com/neovim/nvim-lspconfig\",version=vim.version.range '2.6.0'}})\n> :qa\n> # mocking fail write\n> cd ./data/nvim/site/pack/core/opt/nvim-lspconfig/\n> # 2.7.0\n> git checkout 0203a9608d63eda57679b01e69f33a7b4c34b0d1\n> cd -\n> nvim --clean ./config/nvim/nvim-pack-lock.json\n> # modify version field from \"2.6.0 - 2.6.0\" -> \">=0.0.0\"\n> :w\n> :qa\n> nvim --clean\n> :lua vim.pack.update()\n> ```\n\nThese reproduction steps work as expected:\n- The state on the disk is `v2.7.0`, which is the latest available version.\n- The (manually changed) lockfile says that updating should update to the latest available version.\n- When computing new changes, there are none. Hence the `Same` and \"Nothing to update\". In this case I don't think it is a good idea to write the lockfile with the current state. At least because it would require executing `:write` when there is nothing to update.\n\nTo detect the problem and possible solution, there is `:checkhealth vim.pack`. It does show that there is not synced lockfile. The problem is that its suggested solution only shows how to update if there are changes. Adding a note about more drastic measures (delete an entry and restart) is the good solution here.",
